'''Conférence Internationale Permanente d'Instituts Universitaires de Traducteurs et Interprètes''' (French for ''International Standing Conference of University Institutes of Translators and Interpreters''), abbreviated as '''CIUTI''', is an international academy associating [[translation]] and [[Literary theory|interpretation]] institutes affiliated to universities. Founded in the 1960s, the institution aims at promoting international T&I cooperation in both professional training and academic research.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ciuti.org/ | title=CIUTI | accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>

The establishment of CIUTI was proposed by the universities of [[Geneva University|Geneva]], [[Ruprecht Karl University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]], [[University of Mainz|Mainz/Germersheim]], [[University of Paris|Paris-Sorbonne]], [[Saarland University|Saarbrücken]] and [[University of Trieste|Trieste]], in response to the high demand for competent translators and interpreters after [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ciuti.org/about-us/history/ | title=History | accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>

The CIUTI membership is open to institutions at the level of tertiary education only, and restricted to those who offer programs in translation, interpreting and multilingual communication. A set of high quality standards is attached to membership applications, which involves strict requirements on curriculum structure, research, academic infrastructure and resources of applicant institutions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ciuti.org/join-ciuti/admission-procedure/ | title=Admission procedure | accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref>

