{{refimprove|date=March 2013}} [[File:World Citizen Flag.svg|thumb|The flag of the WSA.]] The '''World Service Authority''' ('''WSA'''), founded in 1954,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2006/03/whats_a_world_passport.1.html |title= What's a World Passport? |accessdate= 10 June 2015 |last= Engber |first= Daniel |date= 24 March 2006 |publisher= Slate}}</ref> is a non-profit organization that claims to educate about and promote "world citizenship", "world law", and [[World Government]]. It is best known for selling [[World Passport]]s.
==Organization== WSA has an office in [[Washington, D.C.]] The office in [[Shanghai]], People's Republic of China, closed on 1 January 2010. {{As of|2017}} attorney David M. Gallup was the president of WSA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7dvt.com/2001/passport-fame |title="Passport To Fame", 7 Days Vermont, 28 March 2001 |publisher=7dvt.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.martindale.com/David-M-Gallup/380116-lawyer.htm |title=Martindale.com, David M. Gallup |publisher=Martindale.com |date=2010-08-10 |accessdate=2017-11-08}}</ref>
==History== The WSA was founded by [[Garry Davis]], a former Broadway actor and [[World War II]] bomber pilot, who officially [[relinquishment of United States nationality|gave up his U.S. citizenship]] in 1948 to live as a "citizen of the world". It was set up to be the administrative agency of the "[[World government|World Government of World Citizens]]" which he declared on 4 September 1953.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldservice.org/gov.html |title=What is the World Government of World Citizens? |publisher=Worldservice.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> The first office was opened in [[New York City]] in 1954. <ref>http://www.worldservice.org/gov.html</ref> In the past, WSA also had offices in [[Basel]], [[London]] and [[Tokyo]]. <ref>http://www.worldservice.org/posipapr.html</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldservice.org/blog/2003/09/50th-anniversary-of-world-citizen.html|title=World Citizen Update: 50th Anniversary of the World Citizen Government|website=www.worldservice.org}}</ref>
==Activities== Besides selling World Passports,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/us/garry-davis-man-of-no-nation-dies-at-91.html|title=Garry Davis, Man of No Nation Who Saw One World of No War, Dies at 91|last=Fox|first=Margalit|date=2013-07-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-05|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the WSA registers customers as "world citizens" and sells "world citizen" identity documents, such as fantasy birth certificates, identity cards, marriage certificates, political asylum cards, "International Exit Visas" and "International Residence Permits".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldservice.org/doc.html |title=World Government Documents (Personal) |publisher=Worldservice.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> The organization's legal department is responsible to assist holders of its documents.<ref>http://worldservice.org/wsaljudc.html</ref> The organization also promotes programs, such as "Mundialization" – declaring cities and towns as "world territories"; "World Syntegrity Project" – an attempt to create a world constitution through meetings of citizens; and other programs.<ref>http://worldservice.org/programs.html?s=2</ref> WSA is also involved in a project to establish a World Court of Human Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcourtofhumanrights.net/home|title=World Court of Human Rights Development Project|website=www.worldcourtofhumanrights.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnx3b3JsZGNvdXJ0b2ZodW1hbnJpZ2h0c3xneDo0N2M3NzMzOWRkNzI5OTUy|title=WCHR Tri-fold.pdf|website=docs.google.com}}</ref> The WSA has also allegedly sold World Government Postal Stamps,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldservice.org/cat.html?s=4#stamps |title=World Service Authority catalog |publisher=Worldservice.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> which, according to Garry Davis, helped to convey thousands of letters between China and [[Taiwan]] in the early 1980s.<ref name="onefilms2001">{{cite web|url=http://www.onefilms.com/garry-davis-herald-tribune-quixotic-quest-article.php|title=International Herald Tribune|author=|date=5 December 2001|publisher=Onefilms.com|accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref>
